# React Compiler Rules

This project has `reactCompiler: true` in `next.config.ts`. The compiler auto-memoizes components, hooks, and expressions. Follow these rules so it can do its job.

## No manual memoization

Do not use `React.memo`, `useMemo`, or `useCallback`. The compiler inserts equivalent caching automatically; manual wrappers conflict or produce redundant work.

```tsx
// BAD
const sorted = useMemo(() => items.toSorted(cmp), [items, cmp]);

// GOOD
const sorted = items.toSorted(cmp);
```

## Never mutate — always create new references

The compiler skips re-renders when references are unchanged. Mutation breaks this.

```ts
// BAD
layers.push(newLayer);
setLayers(layers);

// GOOD
setLayers([...layers, newLayer]);
```

## Never read or write refs during render

Ref access is allowed only inside effects, event handlers, and cleanup functions.

```tsx
// BAD — ref read during render
return <p>{inputRef.current?.value}</p>;

// GOOD — ref read in an effect
useEffect(() => {
  inputRef.current?.focus();
}, []);
```

## Never call hooks conditionally or in loops

Hooks must be called at the top level of a component or custom hook, every render, in the same order.
